    # Generate random weight with sum equal to one
    weight = np.random.random(asset_num)
    weight = weight/np.sum(weight)
    weight_.append(weight)
    # Calculate portfolio std
    std = np.sqrt(np.dot(weight.T, np.dot(var_matrix,weight)))
    std_.append(std)
    # Calculate portfolio return
    port_return = np.dot(return_stock, weight)

Generate different weights and record portfolio return and Tracking Error¶

In [16]:
return_ = []
weight_ = []
TE_ = []
for i in range(10000):
    # Generate random weight with sum equal to one
    weight = np.random.random(asset_num)
    weight = weight/np.sum(weight)
    weight_.append(weight)
    # Calculate portfolio std
    port_std = np.sqrt(np.dot(weight.T, np.dot(var_matrix,weight)))
    # Calculate portfolio return
    port_return = np.dot(return_stock, weight)
    return_.append(port_return)
    # Calculate the correlation between portfolio and benchmark
    portfolio_ret_se = ret_df.dot(weight)
    corr_p_BM = ret_BM_df[BM_ticker].corr(portfolio_ret_se)
    # Calculate tracking error
    TE = np.sqrt(port_std**2+BM_std**2-2*corr_p_BM*port_std*BM_std)
    TE_.append(TE)

Q8. What is the connection between the minimum TE portfolio procedure you derived above and this linear regression procedure? Describe the similarities and differences. Under what scenarios will one be better than the other? Use both mathematics and intuitive reasoning to narrate the answer.¶

  • Minimum TE portfolio procedure and linear regression procedure both applying same idea that minimize the difference of portfolio return and benchmark return
  • Minimum TE portfolio procedure use variance of return difference as metric
  • Linear regression procedure use mean square of return difference as metric
  • According to the metric formulas of both procedures,the major difference is that Minimum TE portfolio takes into account the correlation between assests in portfolio
  • Thus, when the portfolio contain highly correlated assets, Minimum TE portfolio procedure is better than inear regression procedure

In [55]:
# Function which can tell if the quantity matches between two sheets 
def quantities_analyzer(asset_id,trade_data,holding_data):
    df_1 = trade_data.loc[trade_data.asset_id==asset_id,['date','actual_traded_quant','transaction_id']]
    df_2 = holding_data.loc[holding_data.asset_id == asset_id, ['date','quantity']]
    df_1.drop_duplicates(subset=['transaction_id'],inplace=True) # There are some duplicate data in Trade Data sheet
    dff= df_2.merge(df_1,how='outer').fillna(0)
    dff['actual_traded_quant'] = dff['actual_traded_quant'].cumsum()
    # Already having position in this asset 
    bool_1 = dff['quantity'].values[0] + dff['actual_traded_quant'].values[-1] == dff['quantity'].values[-1]
    # Not having any position in this asset
    bool_2 = dff['actual_traded_quant'].values[-1] == dff['quantity'].values[-1]
    return bool_1 or bool_2
